[{"data":1,"prerenderedAt":551},["ShallowReactive",2],{"header-locale:\u002Fen\u002Fnodejs\u002F2022\u002F02\u002F17\u002Fmango-frontend-05-mongodb-cursor-methods\u002F":3,"page:\u002Fen\u002Fnodejs\u002F2022\u002F02\u002F17\u002Fmango-frontend-05-mongodb-cursor-methods\u002F":4,"alt:\u002Fen\u002Fnodejs\u002F2022\u002F02\u002F17\u002Fmango-frontend-05-mongodb-cursor-methods\u002F":3,"prev-next:\u002Fen\u002Fnodejs\u002F2022\u002F02\u002F17\u002Fmango-frontend-05-mongodb-cursor-methods\u002F":528,"related:\u002Fen\u002Fnodejs\u002F2022\u002F02\u002F17\u002Fmango-frontend-05-mongodb-cursor-methods\u002F":537},"\u002Fnodejs\u002F20220217\u002F3658117877\u002F",{"id":5,"title":6,"abbrlink":7,"altUrl":3,"body":8,"category":509,"date":510,"description":511,"extension":512,"lang":513,"meta":514,"navigation":515,"path":516,"readingMinutes":517,"seo":518,"standalone":519,"stem":520,"tags":521,"tldr":525,"updated":510,"url":526,"__hash__":527},"content\u002Fen\u002FNodejs\u002Fmango-frontend-05-mongodb-cursor-methods.md","(5) The Frontend Engineer Forced to Eat Mango - MongoDB CRUD: Read and Its Cursor Methods","1003318064",{"type":9,"value":10,"toc":499},"minimark",[11,16,20,24,32,39,88,94,100,103,106,112,122,150,154,157,162,186,192,198,223,229,234,248,251,260,274,279,284,306,312,322,328,397,403,406,411,433,438,442,445,448,490,495],[12,13,15],"h2",{"id":14},"intro","Intro",[17,18,19],"p",{},"Surprise, right? Turns out Read deserves a second post. The previous one walked through the common Read operators, but in practice you'll usually pair those with a few common Cursor Methods too. So what's a Cursor anyway? Let's find out.",[12,21,23],{"id":22},"cursor-methods","Cursor Methods",[17,25,26,27,31],{},"So what are Cursor Methods? You can think of them as a kind of post-processing. What do I mean by that? Say I search for users who are 25 years old and have a ",[28,29,30],"code",{},"true"," status. Normally that returns 3 results.",[17,33,34,35,38],{},"But once you apply a Cursor Method, you can limit it down to, say, a single result. One common method is ",[28,36,37],{},"limit",", which caps how many documents the query returns:",[40,41,46],"pre",{"className":42,"code":43,"language":44,"meta":45,"style":45},"language-js shiki shiki-themes github-dark-high-contrast","db.users.find({ $and: [{ age: { $eq: 25 } }, { status: false }] }).limit(1)\n","js","",[28,47,48],{"__ignoreMap":45},[49,50,53,57,61,64,68,71,74,77,79,82,85],"span",{"class":51,"line":52},"line",1,[49,54,56],{"class":55},"sMAXC","db.users.",[49,58,60],{"class":59},"sj_SG","find",[49,62,63],{"class":55},"({ $and: [{ age: { $eq: ",[49,65,67],{"class":66},"sCcAr","25",[49,69,70],{"class":55}," } }, { status: ",[49,72,73],{"class":66},"false",[49,75,76],{"class":55}," }] }).",[49,78,37],{"class":59},[49,80,81],{"class":55},"(",[49,83,84],{"class":66},"1",[49,86,87],{"class":55},")\n",[17,89,90,91,93],{},"By default this would output three documents, but because we used ",[28,92,37],{},", only one shows up:",[17,95,96],{},[97,98],"img",{"alt":37,"src":99},"https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FNodejs\u002F%E6%88%AA%E5%9C%96%202022-01-24%2020.57.08.png",[17,101,102],{},"So Cursor Methods are about taking the search results and doing some extra iteration on top of them. Let me list out a few of the common ones.",[104,105,37],"h3",{"id":37},[17,107,108,109,111],{},"We already tried ",[28,110,37],{}," a moment ago, but let me explain it once more.",[17,113,114,115,118,119,121],{},"When you run ",[28,116,117],{},"db.users.find({ $and: [{ age: { $eq: 25 } }, { status: false }] })",", you'd expect three documents back. But if you only want to keep one of those results, you can use ",[28,120,37],{},":",[40,123,124],{"className":42,"code":43,"language":44,"meta":45,"style":45},[28,125,126],{"__ignoreMap":45},[49,127,128,130,132,134,136,138,140,142,144,146,148],{"class":51,"line":52},[49,129,56],{"class":55},[49,131,60],{"class":59},[49,133,63],{"class":55},[49,135,67],{"class":66},[49,137,70],{"class":55},[49,139,73],{"class":66},[49,141,76],{"class":55},[49,143,37],{"class":59},[49,145,81],{"class":55},[49,147,84],{"class":66},[49,149,87],{"class":55},[17,151,152],{},[97,153],{"alt":37,"src":99},[104,155,156],{"id":156},"sort",[17,158,159,161],{},[28,160,156],{}," is exactly what it sounds like — super handy when you want to sort by age. For example, smallest to largest:",[40,163,165],{"className":42,"code":164,"language":44,"meta":45,"style":45},"db.users.find().sort({ age: 1 })\n",[28,166,167],{"__ignoreMap":45},[49,168,169,171,173,176,178,181,183],{"class":51,"line":52},[49,170,56],{"class":55},[49,172,60],{"class":59},[49,174,175],{"class":55},"().",[49,177,156],{"class":59},[49,179,180],{"class":55},"({ age: ",[49,182,84],{"class":66},[49,184,185],{"class":55}," })\n",[17,187,188],{},[97,189],{"alt":190,"src":191},"small to large","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FNodejs\u002F%E6%88%AA%E5%9C%96%202022-01-24%2021.03.53.png",[17,193,194,195,121],{},"Largest to smallest is a little different, because in MongoDB that's ",[28,196,197],{},"-1",[40,199,201],{"className":42,"code":200,"language":44,"meta":45,"style":45},"db.users.find().sort({ age: -1 })\n",[28,202,203],{"__ignoreMap":45},[49,204,205,207,209,211,213,215,219,221],{"class":51,"line":52},[49,206,56],{"class":55},[49,208,60],{"class":59},[49,210,175],{"class":55},[49,212,156],{"class":59},[49,214,180],{"class":55},[49,216,218],{"class":217},"sWyjQ","-",[49,220,84],{"class":66},[49,222,185],{"class":55},[17,224,225],{},[97,226],{"alt":227,"src":228},"large to small","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FNodejs\u002F%E6%88%AA%E5%9C%96%202022-01-24%2021.05.39.png",[17,230,231,232,121],{},"Quick note to drive the point home for ",[28,233,156],{},[235,236,237,243],"ul",{},[238,239,240,241],"li",{},"Smallest to largest is ",[28,242,84],{},[238,244,245,246],{},"Largest to smallest is ",[28,247,197],{},[104,249,250],{"id":250},"count",[17,252,253,254,256,257,259],{},"Some people see ",[28,255,250],{}," and assume it's a method for tallying things up, but ",[28,258,250],{}," actually just returns the number of documents. For example, my database currently has 14 documents, so this method returns 14 directly:",[40,261,263],{"className":42,"code":262,"language":44,"meta":45,"style":45},"db.users.count()\n",[28,264,265],{"__ignoreMap":45},[49,266,267,269,271],{"class":51,"line":52},[49,268,56],{"class":55},[49,270,250],{"class":59},[49,272,273],{"class":55},"()\n",[17,275,276],{},[97,277],{"alt":250,"src":278},"https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FNodejs\u002F%E6%88%AA%E5%9C%96%202022-01-24%2021.17.32.png",[17,280,281,283],{},[28,282,250],{}," can also be combined with a Query to count matches. Say I want to find out how many people are 25 years old:",[40,285,287],{"className":42,"code":286,"language":44,"meta":45,"style":45},"db.users.find({ age: 25 }).count()\n",[28,288,289],{"__ignoreMap":45},[49,290,291,293,295,297,299,302,304],{"class":51,"line":52},[49,292,56],{"class":55},[49,294,60],{"class":59},[49,296,180],{"class":55},[49,298,67],{"class":66},[49,300,301],{"class":55}," }).",[49,303,250],{"class":59},[49,305,273],{"class":55},[17,307,308],{},[97,309],{"alt":310,"src":311},"count matches","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FNodejs\u002F%E6%88%AA%E5%9C%96%202022-01-24%2021.21.02.png",[17,313,314,315,317,318,321],{},"So ",[28,316,250],{}," is basically like the ",[28,319,320],{},"length"," of an array.",[17,323,324,325,121],{},"If you want to actually compute something over a field like age, you'll need a different approach called ",[28,326,327],{},"aggregate",[40,329,331],{"className":42,"code":330,"language":44,"meta":45,"style":45},"db.users.aggregate([\n  {\n    $group: {\n      _id: null,\n      ageTotal: { $sum: \"$age\" }\n    }\n  }\n])\n",[28,332,333,342,348,354,366,379,385,391],{"__ignoreMap":45},[49,334,335,337,339],{"class":51,"line":52},[49,336,56],{"class":55},[49,338,327],{"class":59},[49,340,341],{"class":55},"([\n",[49,343,345],{"class":51,"line":344},2,[49,346,347],{"class":55},"  {\n",[49,349,351],{"class":51,"line":350},3,[49,352,353],{"class":55},"    $group: {\n",[49,355,357,360,363],{"class":51,"line":356},4,[49,358,359],{"class":55},"      _id: ",[49,361,362],{"class":66},"null",[49,364,365],{"class":55},",\n",[49,367,369,372,376],{"class":51,"line":368},5,[49,370,371],{"class":55},"      ageTotal: { $sum: ",[49,373,375],{"class":374},"sTRMh","\"$age\"",[49,377,378],{"class":55}," }\n",[49,380,382],{"class":51,"line":381},6,[49,383,384],{"class":55},"    }\n",[49,386,388],{"class":51,"line":387},7,[49,389,390],{"class":55},"  }\n",[49,392,394],{"class":51,"line":393},8,[49,395,396],{"class":55},"])\n",[17,398,399],{},[97,400],{"alt":401,"src":402},"ageTotal","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FNodejs\u002F%E6%88%AA%E5%9C%96%202022-01-24%2021.41.31.png",[104,404,405],{"id":405},"skip",[17,407,408,410],{},[28,409,405],{}," is basically the \"skip over\" concept — it means how many documents you want to jump past. For example, I want to start outputting from the 10th document onward:",[40,412,414],{"className":42,"code":413,"language":44,"meta":45,"style":45},"db.users.find().skip(10)\n",[28,415,416],{"__ignoreMap":45},[49,417,418,420,422,424,426,428,431],{"class":51,"line":52},[49,419,56],{"class":55},[49,421,60],{"class":59},[49,423,175],{"class":55},[49,425,405],{"class":59},[49,427,81],{"class":55},[49,429,430],{"class":66},"10",[49,432,87],{"class":55},[17,434,435],{},[97,436],{"alt":405,"src":437},"https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FNodejs\u002F%E6%88%AA%E5%9C%96%202022-01-24%2021.44.03.png",[12,439,441],{"id":440},"chaining","Chaining",[17,443,444],{},"Cursor Methods all support chaining. What's chaining? It's similar to writing jQuery.",[17,446,447],{},"MongoDB runs the result left to right. For example, skip the first five documents, then limit to two documents, and finally sort by age from largest to smallest:",[40,449,451],{"className":42,"code":450,"language":44,"meta":45,"style":45},"db.users.find().skip(5).limit(2).sort({ age: -1 })\n",[28,452,453],{"__ignoreMap":45},[49,454,455,457,459,461,463,465,468,471,473,475,478,480,482,484,486,488],{"class":51,"line":52},[49,456,56],{"class":55},[49,458,60],{"class":59},[49,460,175],{"class":55},[49,462,405],{"class":59},[49,464,81],{"class":55},[49,466,467],{"class":66},"5",[49,469,470],{"class":55},").",[49,472,37],{"class":59},[49,474,81],{"class":55},[49,476,477],{"class":66},"2",[49,479,470],{"class":55},[49,481,156],{"class":59},[49,483,180],{"class":55},[49,485,218],{"class":217},[49,487,84],{"class":66},[49,489,185],{"class":55},[17,491,492],{},[97,493],{"alt":440,"src":494},"https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FNodejs\u002F%E6%88%AA%E5%9C%96%202022-01-24%2021.49.14.png",[496,497,498],"style",{},"html pre.shiki code .sMAXC, html code.shiki .sMAXC{--shiki-default:#F0F3F6}html pre.shiki code .sj_SG, html code.shiki .sj_SG{--shiki-default:#DBB7FF}html pre.shiki code .sCcAr, html code.shiki .sCcAr{--shiki-default:#91CBFF}html .default .shiki span {color: var(--shiki-default);background: var(--shiki-default-bg);font-style: var(--shiki-default-font-style);font-weight: var(--shiki-default-font-weight);text-decoration: var(--shiki-default-text-decoration);}html .shiki span {color: var(--shiki-default);background: var(--shiki-default-bg);font-style: var(--shiki-default-font-style);font-weight: var(--shiki-default-font-weight);text-decoration: var(--shiki-default-text-decoration);}html pre.shiki code .sWyjQ, html code.shiki .sWyjQ{--shiki-default:#FF9492}html pre.shiki code .sTRMh, html code.shiki .sTRMh{--shiki-default:#ADDCFF}",{"title":45,"searchDepth":344,"depth":344,"links":500},[501,502,508],{"id":14,"depth":344,"text":15},{"id":22,"depth":344,"text":23,"children":503},[504,505,506,507],{"id":37,"de